Steadfast Group | Asia Pacific
WHAT'S CHANGEDSteadfast Group (SDF.AX)FromPrice TargetA'S6.71

SDF is a step closer to a global insurance ecosystem with acquisition of Novum, a US wholesale brokerage with digital marketplace capabilities. We see \(\sim 8.5\%\) underlying EPS CAGR into FY28E. SDF offers value on \(\sim 16.5x\) FY27E NPAT \(\mathsf{P} / \mathsf{E}\) .

Earnings growth: SDF's FY26 guidance for underlying NPAT of A\$315- 325m equates to \(6 - 10\%\) growth, and bakes in \(3\%\) ppt growth from M&A (vs. \(2\%\) ppt in FY25) and 3- \(7\%\) ppt organic (based on \(3 - 5\%\) pricing increases in Australia). We forecast growth towards the upper end with \(9\%\) given SDF's multiple growth options and trackrecord of conservative guidance. SDF also completed several deals at the end of FY25 and made its first US acquisition in August, so we think it has good visibility on FY26 M&A growth. Our underlying EPS (NPAT) falls \(3\%\) on lower topline growth in FY26E, though is only \(1\%\) lower in FY27- 28E. Our PT rises by \(\sim 0.5\%\) to A\$6.74.

SDF has a substantial US market opportunity: The US broker market is \(\sim \cup S\) \(\updownarrow 200bn\) vs \(\sim \cup S\) \(\updownarrow 24bn\) in AUS. We see at least three avenues for growth. One is growing the ISU network. It now has 241 members, up from \(\sim 225\) at the October 2023 acquisition. ISU Lite will launch within 12 months and allow smaller brokers to join. Second is only \(30\%\) of ISU's GWP volume is via master agreements generating revenues for ISU, with substantial opportunity to increase this. These are both capital- light options. Growing ISU may require some investment in tech & analytics, but SDF emphasised that ISU can reinvest to self fund its growth. The third growth avenue is SDF making US acquisitions.

Novum - network of networks: SDF has bought a majority stake in Novum, a US MGA and wholesale brokerage with digital marketplace capabilities. It is connected with 8,000 agents/brokers and wrote \(\sim \cup S\) \(\updownarrow 100m\) GWP in FY25. We think this is a strategically powerful acquisition - it brings both US and global network leverage via the marketplace past- tracks bringing existing SDF underwriting agencies into the US (e.g., cyber) and connects SDF's Lloyds wholesale solutions with ISU members' brokers. It also becomes ISU's program management platform in the US.

Growth in Australia: We think underwriting agencies or MGAs continue to offer powerful growth options and extend a broker's ecosystem. Sure Insurance stands out as it is starting to grow in direct Home & Contents beyond its starting QLD footprint to expand nationally. SDF has also identified potential to acquire A\$441m EBITA from its current Australasian Network in trapped capital, with A\$183m of this from existing equity brokers and the rest from potential opportunities from non- equity brokers. For comparison, our FY26 forecast EBITA for the Broking division is A \$483m at a \(38\%\) margin. An area to be mindful of is regulatory or ACCC developments on dealing with serial or 'creeping' acquisitions.

Attractive organic and acquisition growth options

SDF is the market leader in Australia, with scale and a one- stop- shop for broking needs. Well positioned to benefit from the stronger for longer pricing cycle. Broker network shores up acquisition pipeline, though domestic competition and regulatory oversight is increasing. Attractive global growth options both in the US (though early stage) and building organic footprint at Lloyd's. We do note unusually high corporate costs, which somewhat limits margin expansion and means true divisional contributions are unclear. Visionary founder presence, though this adds key- man risk. Valuation is in line with or below high growth financial peers.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
Secular Growth: Positive Self- help: Positive

Hard market persists, driven by elevated insurance industry losses and stubbornly high claims inflation. Positive jaws across Broking & Underwriting. Acquisitions are in line with historical multiples and value- enhancing; pipeline strong. Domestic & overseas network growth accelerates, driven by improvements in Insurtech adoption.

Commercial insurance pricing tracks towards mid- single digit levels in the near- term supporting earnings growth. Strong margins are maintained in Broking and Underwriting Agencies. Inorganic growth achieved via domestic trapped capital program and patient global expansion.

Commercial insurance pricing softens significantly, leading to margin compression across Broking and Underwriting Agencies. Competition for new broker acquisitions intensifies leading to a reduced pipeline and higher multiples paid. Global expansion plans do not eventuate.
